Evaluation and rationale:
- Jagged Little Pill aligns strongly with the positive items above. It’s a mid‑90s alt‑rock album built around immediate, radio‑ready singles (e.g., “You Oughta Know,” “Ironic,” “Hand in My Pocket”) that feature punchy drums, crunchy guitars and big vocal hooks. The production balances aggressive, high‑energy rock moments with quieter acoustic passages, creating the dynamic contrast I prize. The CD‑era sequencing and front‑to‑back coherence suit my preference for discs that maintain momentum and reward attentive, uninterrupted listening on physical media. Alanis’s raw, confessional, dynamic vocal performances deliver the slightly rough edges and revealing detail I enjoy hearing on a CD.
