The user updates his self-description as follows: I now favor bright, guitar‑forward AOR with dry, center‑front vocals, minimal reverb, crisp separation, snappy transients and tight sequencing; punchy, groove‑forward low end and tasteful harmony stacking that supports — not competes with — a hook‑first lead. I prefer mixes that are studio‑tight and revealing rather than roomy or breathy; vocal consonants and lead intimacy are paramount.
Retained from earlier tastes: low‑compression mastering, preserved transient snap, modest analogue warmth/tape character, intimate midrange, clear stereo imaging, sparse overdubs when they serve clarity, and tight guitar/bass interplay that supports lyrical delivery.
Dislikes: piano‑forward, live‑ambience mixes that soften hooks or render vocals breathy/distant; dense harmony stacking that buries the lead; heavy remaster polish or subtle limiting that reduces microdynamics; brickwall limiting; muddy bass that masks mids; over‑produced cinematic arrangements.

